<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org5a387be">
<h4 id="org5a387be">Dial-up</h4>
<ul>
<li>modem connection over standard phone line</li>
<li>still possible!</li>
<li>&ldquo;Phone and modem&rdquo; in Control Panel</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org62d92f9">
<h4 id="org62d92f9">Wireless</h4>
<ul>
<li class="fragment appear">Network name - SSID</li>
<li class="fragment appear">Encryption type:
<ul>
<li>TKIP</li>
<li>AES</li>

</ul></li>
<li class="fragment appear">WPA2</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgf79ad75">
<h4 id="orgf79ad75">Wired connections</h4>
<ul>
<li>Ethernet</li>

</ul>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/3-1-UTP-STP.png" alt="3-1-UTP-STP.png" width="90%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 16: </span>Ethernet cables</p>
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org9a1b835">
<h4 id="org9a1b835">WWAN (Cellular)</h4>
<ul>
<li>Wireless Wide Area Network</li>
<li>built-in mobile technology</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgbe80019">
<h3 id="orgbe80019">Proxy settings</h3>
<ul>
<li>Usually set up by larger organizations</li>
<li>Proxy functions as a go-between:
<ul>
<li>local caching of data increases speed</li>
<li>Can restrict network access</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orge1fe1a0">
<h3 id="orge1fe1a0">Remote Assistance</h3>
<ul>
<li>Home editions</li>
<li>One-time remote access</li>
<li>Allows one way control by technician to support user
<ul>
<li>Firewall must allow to pass through</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org1d2f7fe">
<h3 id="org1d2f7fe">Remote Desktop Connection</h3>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/1-8-RemoteDesktopConnection.png" alt="1-8-RemoteDesktopConnection.png" width="60%" align="left">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 17: </span>Remote Desktop Connection</p>
</div>
<ul>
<li>Allows you to use your computer from somewhere else</li>

</ul>

<ul>
<li class="fragment appear">Enabled on the Remote tab on the System Properties window
<ul>
<li>ensure that both computers have this enabled</li>
<li>identify the target machine by name or IP</li>
<li><code>MTSC</code> (Microsoft Terminal Services Client)
<ul>
<li>port &#x2026; 3389!</li>
<li>Well engineered service - can account for bandwidth problems, use local resources</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orge3062da">
<h3 id="orge3062da">Home vs. Work vs. Public network settings</h3>
<ul>
<li>Set when configuring network connection
<ul>
<li><b>Home</b> - allows your shared data to be discoverable by others on network</li>
<li><b>Work</b> - Usually implies that a Domain is in use</li>
<li><b>Public</b> - Most restrictive</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orge040bfa">
<h3 id="orge040bfa">Firewall settings</h3>
<ul>
<li>From Control Panel, Search or Run</li>
<li>Filters web traffic using TCP port numbers
<ul>
<li>Windows Firewall simple, user-friendly, no IPtables</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org76f7ebe">
<h4 id="org76f7ebe">Configuration</h4>
<ul>
<li>Pre-configured rules, usually requires no changes for simple home use</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgd51e48f">
<h4 id="orgd51e48f">Exceptions</h4>
<ul>
<li>Can make Exceptions on the fly if connectivity problems
<ul>
<li>Done per app</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org90427f7">
<h4 id="org90427f7">Enabling/disabling Windows Firewall</h4>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/1-8-WindowsFirewall.png" alt="1-8-WindowsFirewall.png" width="90%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 18: </span>Windows Defender Firewall</p>
</div>
<ul>
<li>If connection problems, can diagnose by turning off <span style="color:red;">very briefly!</span></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org7584693">
<h3 id="org7584693">Configuring an alternative IP address in Windows</h3>
<ul>
<li>Usually, IP address determine by DHCP
<ul>
<li>But in some situations may want to set uniquely</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org7191a48">
<h4 id="org7191a48">IP addressing</h4>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/1-8-AlternativeIPaddress.png" alt="1-8-AlternativeIPaddress.png" width="50%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 19: </span>IP addressing</p>
</div>
<ul>
<li>IPv4 - 32-bit address</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org3ab769c">
<h4 id="org3ab769c">Subnet mask</h4>
<ul>
<li>Identifies the network
<ul>
<li>which of the remaining octets identify the host:
<ul>
<li>e.g. <code>255.255.255.0</code> three octets for the network, eight bits for the host</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org180545a">
<h4 id="org180545a">DNS</h4>
<ul>
<li>Here, can set the IP address of the DNS server</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org18822e5">
<h4 id="org18822e5">Gateway</h4>
<ul>
<li>The device that provides access to the Internet</li>
<li>At your home, probably your router</li>
<li>Gateway address must be correct on the workstation or it will not be able to connect to the network!</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org58dc60a">
<h3 id="org58dc60a">Network card properties</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org58dc60a">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org94321ef">
<h4 id="org94321ef">Half duplex/full duplex/auto</h4>
<ul>
<li>Half-duplex: one way transport of data</li>
<li>Full-duplex: both ways</li>
<li>Auto-negotiation: communication between devices</li>

</ul>


<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/1-8-HalfFullDuplex.png" alt="1-8-HalfFullDuplex.png" width="30%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 20: </span>Half duplex &amp; Full duplex</p>
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org6489165">
<h4 id="org6489165">Wake-on-LAN</h4>
<ul>
<li>Computers can be woken up from low power mode, in some rare configurations from being completely powered off</li>
<li>&ldquo;Magic packet&rdquo; sent from another device on LAN</li>
<li>Wired connections only!</li>

</ul>
<div class="column" style="float:left; width:50%">

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/1-8-Wake-on-LAN.png" alt="1-8-Wake-on-LAN.png">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 21: </span>WOL can be enabled in the BIOS</p>
</div>
</div>


<div class="column" style="float:right; width:50%">

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/1-8-enableWOL.png" alt="1-8-enableWOL.png">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 22: </span>Or sometimes from Network Management</p>
</div>
</div>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/1-8-SendingAmagicPacket.png" alt="1-8-SendingAmagicPacket.png" width="30%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 23: </span>Sending a magic packet</p>
</div>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org4fc3acb">
<h4 id="org4fc3acb">QoS</h4>
<ul>
<li>Quality of Service - configure priority of services on the network</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgce19382">
<h4 id="orgce19382">BIOS (on-board NIC)</h4>
<ul>
<li>When the network connection device is built into the motherboard, some things are configured in the BIOS</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
</section>
<section>
<section id="slide-org1dd78ed">
<h2 id="org1dd78ed">1.9 – Given a scenario, use features and tools of the Mac OS and Linux client/desktop operating systems.</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org1dd78ed">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org7e33dc1">
<h3 id="org7e33dc1">Best practices</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org7e33dc1">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org4958c13">
<h4 id="org4958c13">Scheduled backups</h4>
<ul>
<li>Should be routine and scheduled</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org04eb177">
<h4 id="org04eb177">Scheduled disk maintenance</h4>
<ul>
<li>In macOS, through Disk Utility App
<ul>
<li>Permissions can be verified</li>
<li>These can become corrupted over long use</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgdee1460">
<h4 id="orgdee1460">System updates/App Store</h4>
<ul>
<li>In Linux done on command line
<ul>
<li>Ubuntu: <code>sudo apt-get update</code></li>
<li>Red Hat / CentOS: <code>yum update</code></li>
<li>Linux desktops have GUI apps for this</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org5a80677">
<h4 id="org5a80677">Patch management</h4>
<ul>
<li>macOS - done through App Store</li>
<li>Linux - through above update system</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org8fec9ae">
<h4 id="org8fec9ae">Driver/firmware updates</h4>
<ul>
<li>as in last slide</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgd23c6f3">
<h4 id="orgd23c6f3">Antivirus/Anti-malware updates</h4>
<ul>
<li>Although macOS and Linux tend to have fewer security problems, people do sometimes install antivirus / antimalware</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org204d4a8">
<h3 id="org204d4a8">Tools</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org204d4a8">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgf5b9949">
<h4 id="orgf5b9949">Backup/Time Machine</h4>
<ul>
<li>macOS utility for regular backups</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org6697e66">
<h3 id="org6697e66">Features</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org6697e66">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgbd85557">
<h4 id="orgbd85557">Multiple desktops/Mission Control</h4>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgd2f5c3b">
<h4 id="orgd2f5c3b">Key Chain</h4>
<ul>
<li>password management</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org99f7200">
<h4 id="org99f7200">Spot Light</h4>
<ul>
<li>maintains directory of apps</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org75374a0">
<h4 id="org75374a0">iCloud</h4>
<ul>
<li>Apple&rsquo;s cloud storage</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orge16c818">
<h4 id="orge16c818">Gestures</h4>
<ul>
<li>Cool things you can do on your trackpad</li>
<li>Configured in System PReferences / Trackpad</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org1a78a4f">
<h4 id="org1a78a4f">Finder</h4>
<ul>
<li>macOS version of Windows File Explorer</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org59439d6">
<h4 id="org59439d6">Dock</h4>
<ul>
<li>Bar with application shortcuts, usually on the bottom
<ul>
<li>But can be moved</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org92865e7">
<h4 id="org92865e7">Boot Camp</h4>
<ul>
<li>Allows the boot of different operating systems</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org7f215fe">
<h3 id="org7f215fe">Basic Linux commands</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org7f215fe">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orga6d7cde">
<h4 id="orga6d7cde"><code>man</code></h4>
<ul>
<li>in most Linux / Unix distributions, this gives you the manual for a function</li>
<li>format: <code>man [command]</code>
<ul>
<li>just like <code>help</code> in Windows Command line</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgb90451b">
<h4 id="orgb90451b"><code>ls</code></h4>
<ul>
<li>listing of files in directory</li>
<li>Like <code>dir</code> in Windows command line</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgb97e099">
<h4 id="orgb97e099"><code>grep</code></h4>
<ul>
<li>macOS / Linux search operator
<ul>
<li>can be complex or simple</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org9e798d2">
<h4 id="org9e798d2"><code>cd</code></h4>
<ul>
<li>Change directory</li>
<li>Just like in Windows CLI!</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org3d23477">
<h4 id="org3d23477"><code>shutdown</code></h4>
<ul>
<li>As it says</li>
<li>With different operators:
<ul>
<li>i.e. <code>shutdown -r</code> restarts the machine</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgd78aac9">
<h4 id="orgd78aac9"><code>pwd</code> vs. <code>passwd</code></h4>
<ul>
<li>People get very confused about this, understandably!
<ul>
<li><code>passwd</code> changes your password</li>
<li><code>pwd</code> gives you the &ldquo;present working directory&rdquo;
<ul>
<li>Tells you where you are in the filesystem</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org0c4bf95">
<h4 id="org0c4bf95"><code>mv</code></h4>
<ul>
<li>moves a file, renames a file if it stays in the same directory</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgbae96b8">
<h4 id="orgbae96b8"><code>cp</code></h4>
<ul>
<li>copy: source and destination can be specified.</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgde1907e">
<h4 id="orgde1907e"><code>rm</code></h4>
<ul>
<li>delete or remove files</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org55a3d3f">
<h4 id="org55a3d3f"><code>chmod</code></h4>
<ul>
<li>Linux / macOS only (no equivalent in Windows)</li>
<li>Changes the <b>mode</b> of files - permissions</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org4aa0a5b">
<h4 id="org4aa0a5b"><code>chown</code></h4>
<ul>
<li>Change ownership of file / directory</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org898e734">
<h4 id="org898e734"><code>iwconfig/ifconfig</code></h4>
<ul>
<li>Network configuration commands 
<ul>
<li>Like <code>ipconfig</code> on Windows</li>
<li><code>iwconfig</code> is the wireless configuration, <code>ifconfig</code> is the wired configuration (InterFace CONFIGuration)</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgb9a3820">
<h4 id="orgb9a3820"><code>ps</code></h4>
<ul>
<li>&ldquo;Process status&rdquo; - displays running commands and processes, identifies them by their Process ID (PID)</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgcb0ad8c">
<h4 id="orgcb0ad8c"><code>su</code> / <code>sudo</code></h4>
<ul>
<li>Permits a <b>su</b> bstitute user to &ldquo;do&rdquo; a command</li>
<li><code>sudo</code> user is the &ldquo;super user&rdquo; 
<ul>
<li>analogous to &ldquo;elevated privilege&rdquo; in Windows</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org2be2afb">
<h4 id="org2be2afb"><code>apt-get</code></h4>
<ul>
<li>In some versions of Linux used to retrieve, install, remove packages</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org253ed42">
<h4 id="org253ed42"><code>vi</code></h4>
<ul>
<li>Simple text editor (I prefer <code>nano</code>)</li>
<li>I make fun of Vi, but it is so tiny and it is always there, no matter what weird little Linux distribution you are in</li>
<li>So maybe, probably worth learning (but not for the A+!)</li>

</ul>
<div class="column" style="float:left; width:55%">

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/1-9-vim.png" alt="1-9-vim.png">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 24: </span>Vi / Vim</p>
</div>
</div>

<div class="column" style="float:right; width:40%">

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/1-9-vimCheatSheet.png" alt="1-9-vimCheatSheet.png">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 25: </span>Seriously, look at this, it&rsquo;s crazy</p>
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org699041d">
<h4 id="org699041d"><code>dd</code></h4>
<ul>
<li>&ldquo;data duplicator&rdquo;
<ul>
<li>Used to back up data over network, or to drives, CDs, etc</li>
<li>Very powerful, can back up entire (and large) drives</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orge915a93">
<h4 id="orge915a93"><code>kill</code></h4>
<ul>
<li>Halts a program or process</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
</section>
<section>
<section id="slide-org749f9f9">
<h2 id="org749f9f9">2.1 – Summarize the importance of physical security measures.</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org749f9f9">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orga11a3e2">
<h3 id="orga11a3e2">Mantrap</h3>
<ul>
<li>Area of controlled access between two secured areas</li>
<li>Small room with two doors, for example</li>

</ul>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/2-1-mantrap.png" alt="2-1-mantrap.png" width="75%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 26: </span>Physical security - mantrap</p>
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org33ef960">
<h3 id="org33ef960">Badge reader</h3>
<ul>
<li>Access is provided through security badges that contain coded data that identifies users to the security system.</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org2f5b2a9">
<h3 id="org2f5b2a9">Smart card</h3>
<ul>
<li>Smart cards are another way to deliver security tokens to the system.</li>
<li>Can both send and receive data, allowing the card and the card reader to verify each other</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org6b22ffd">
<h3 id="org6b22ffd">Security guard</h3>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/2-1-SecurityGurad.png" alt="2-1-SecurityGurad.png" width="30%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 27: </span>Some kind of guard</p>
</div>
<ul>
<li>Can be effective</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgdfdb3d1">
<h3 id="orgdfdb3d1">Door lock</h3>
<ul>
<li>Locking doors seem like a simple task, but it can be complicated!
<ul>
<li>Keys can be copied if left unattended</li>
<li>Locks can be picked granting unauthorized access</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgdad65a2">
<h3 id="orgdad65a2">Biometric locks</h3>
<ul>
<li>Using a person’s unique personal attributes such as their Iris, Fingerprint, or Voice to authenticate is known as <b>biometrics</b></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgb7cad56">
<h3 id="orgb7cad56">Hardware tokens</h3>
<ul>
<li>Tokens are a security component necessary for devices to communicate and provide the holder of the token the appropriate access level.</li>
<li>Card reader, magnetic stripe, etc</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org0e3e142">
<h3 id="org0e3e142">Cable locks</h3>
<ul>
<li>Cable locks are used to secure valuable items, that can easily be removed from the workplace.</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org861d0ce">
<h3 id="org861d0ce">Server locks</h3>
<ul>
<li>To prevent unauthorized users from opening a server case</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org9d9c8ee">
<h3 id="org9d9c8ee">USB locks</h3>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/2-1-USBlock.png" alt="2-1-USBlock.png" width="70%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 28: </span>USB lock</p>
</div>
<ul>
<li>These can prevent unauthorized use of a USB port
<ul>
<li>As you may recall, USB ports can be used to boot an outside operating system and can compromise the security of the OS.</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org5ff020b">
<h3 id="org5ff020b">Privacy screen</h3>
<ul>
<li>Privacy filters are employed by users who work in close proximity to others and require security from &ldquo;shoulder surfing&rdquo;</li>
<li>Reduces viewing angle of monitor</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
</section>
<section>
<section id="slide-org4c81fc2">
<h2 id="org4c81fc2">2.2 – Explain logical security concepts.</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org4c81fc2">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgd10ef09">
<h3 id="orgd10ef09">Active Directory</h3>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/2-2-ActiveDirectory.png" alt="2-2-ActiveDirectory.png" width="80%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 29: </span>Active Directory diagram of effective field</p>
</div>
<ul>
<li>Not really a single service anymore 
<ul>
<li>Now describes broad range of services and related databases for identity-related services</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgafa524c">
<h4 id="orgafa524c">Login script</h4>
<ul>
<li>When a user logs in, a list of commands are executed
<ul>
<li>Batch files, PowerShell scripts, etc that set up the user&rsquo;s identity in the organization&rsquo;s IT infrastructure</li>
<li>i.e. access to network shares, servers, email, etc</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org8dbafaf">
<h4 id="org8dbafaf">Domain</h4>
<ul>
<li>The Active Directory organizational hierarchy
<ul>
<li>Often under single internet domain, i.e. Pepsi.com, GMU.edu, Healthcare.gov, etc</li>
<li>But can encompass more sites</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org4c0e101">
<h4 id="org4c0e101">Organizational Units</h4>
<ul>
<li><b>OU</b> - can contain one or more user groups
<ul>
<li>Allows the simplification of the hierarchy of user roles within the network infrastructure</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org6a054e0">
<h4 id="org6a054e0">Group Policy/Updates</h4>
<ul>
<li>Domain resources (workstations, user profiles, privileges,etc</li>
<li>These are controlled by the group policies of the Organizational Unit</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgfd94739">
<h4 id="orgfd94739">Home Folder</h4>
<ul>
<li>A regular home user (such as yourself) saves files locally to their home folder (i.e. <code>C:\Users\[yourname]\Documents</code>)
<ul>
<li>In an enterprise setup, user&rsquo;s <b>home folders</b> can be on a network share, and thus available to the user wherever they go in the organization</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgf624f33">
<h4 id="orgf624f33">Folder redirection</h4>
<ul>
<li>The process in which Active Directory changes the users <b>home folder</b> from their workstation to a network share</li>
<li>This simplifies management and backup requirements
<ul>
<li>Don&rsquo;t have to make a trip out to the user&rsquo;s computer to back up their files</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org7c7b24e">
<h3 id="org7c7b24e">Software tokens</h3>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/2-2-SoftwareToken.png" alt="2-2-SoftwareToken.png" width="30%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 30: </span>Software token on a smartphone</p>
</div>
<ul>
<li>Generated security component used for authentication
<ul>
<li>Devices synchronized with server</li>
<li>Can be cards, or software on phones / mobile devices</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org35df1cc">
<h3 id="org35df1cc">MDM policies - BYOD vs corporate owned</h3>
<ul>
<li>Mobile Device Management:
<ul>
<li>Corporate policy that manages personally-owned vs corporate-owned devices</li>
<li>Organization may require the installation of security apps in employee&rsquo;s phone under a BYOD (Bring Yoour Own Device) protocol</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org5c10dae">
<h3 id="org5c10dae">Port security</h3>
<ul>
<li>Used on switches and routers when connected devices communicate with each other over the network</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgb01d079">
<h3 id="orgb01d079">MAC address filtering</h3>
<ul>
<li>Using a device&rsquo;s MAC address to permit or deny access
<ul>
<li>Remember this is not foolproof!  MAC addresses can be changed and spoofed</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org139705f">
<h3 id="org139705f">Certificates</h3>
<ul>
<li>Digital certificates serve to authorize users and servers</li>
<li>Valid Certificate Authority is what guarantees encryption in <code>https</code> protocol and gives you that nice padlock at the top of your browser</li>

</ul>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/2-2-httpsLockPepsiDotCom.png" alt="2-2-httpsLockPepsiDotCom.png" width="0%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 31: </span>encryption verification</p>
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgaf55ea3">
<h3 id="orgaf55ea3">Antivirus/Anti-malware</h3>
<ul>
<li>Especially in an enterprise context, this kind of security is paramount
<ul>
<li>These programs will examine behavior and content of files against known threats</li>
<li>Virus and malware definitions must be updated on a regular basis</li>
<li>Best done centrally, like other software updates</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgd26ae1c">
<h3 id="orgd26ae1c">Firewalls - hardware vs software</h3>
<ul>
<li>Barrier between the dangerous outside network and the LAN / individual computers</li>
<li><b>Hardware firewall</b> - often found as a part of routers
<ul>
<li>Filters all traffic allowed onto network</li>
<li>Hardware firewall only inspects inbound traffic</li>

</ul></li>
<li><b>Software firewall</b> - on individual workstations, usually, such as Windows Defender Firewall</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org5ceb4fc">
<h3 id="org5ceb4fc">User authentication/strong passwords</h3>
<ul>
<li>The first line of security on a network or device
<ul>
<li>Best &ldquo;strong&rdquo; passwords made by password generators
<ul>
<li>COMPTIA still recommends those kinds of &ldquo;strong&rdquo; passwords with different character types, upper-case, lower-case, etc: <code>e5wd#*Ljp2B9G7!y</code> for example</li>
<li>But, here&rsquo;s a good comic:</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/2-2-xkcdPasswordStrip.png" alt="2-2-xkcdPasswordStrip.png" width="99%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 32: </span>An instructive xkcd comic</p>
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org1acfb83">
<h3 id="org1acfb83">Multifactor authentication</h3>
<ul>
<li>Strong password along with another form of identification / knowledge is superior to a password alone
<ul>
<li>Mantra of multifactor identification:
<ul>
<li>something you know, something you have, something you are, something you do</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgf0e6101">
<h3 id="orgf0e6101">Directory permissions</h3>
<ul>
<li>In both Linux and Windows, permissions and rights can be determined at the levels of individual directories and files
<ul>
<li>Can prevent accidental / unauthorized deletion or modification</li>
<li><b>NTFS</b> - Windows file system format
<ul>
<li>very granular levels of permissions, bu not always obvious to user</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org7b3c5e0">
<h3 id="org7b3c5e0">VPN</h3>
<ul>
<li><b>Virtual Private Network</b> Communicating securely over an insecure pathway</li>
<li>Secure, encrypted tunnel between remote users and the private network of a corporation, enterprise, or home</li>

</ul>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/2-2-VPN-overview-wiki.png" alt="2-2-VPN-overview-wiki.png" width="60%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 33: </span>VPN diagram</p>
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgea4c1d2">
<h3 id="orgea4c1d2">DLP</h3>
<ul>
<li><b>Data Loss Prevention</b> - software and hardware mechanisms to check emails going in and out</li>
<li>It is about data <i>security</i> not backing up data</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgc9e443d">
<h3 id="orgc9e443d">Access control lists</h3>
<ul>
<li>A database of users and devices that are explicitly allowed to access certain networks or devices</li>
<li>Can be filtered by: users, IP addresses, port numbers</li>
<li>Some organizations ban entire <i>regions</i> from accessing their network</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orge65c580">
<h3 id="orge65c580">Email filtering</h3>
<ul>
<li>To reduce spam and unwanted emails</li>
<li>Can scan and block malicious code in emails, phishing, etc</li>
<li>Often done by your email service, whether it is Google, Microsoft, Yahoo, or even AOL (&#9785;)</li>
<li>Organizations will have their own protocols on top of this</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orge699109">
<h3 id="orge699109">Trusted/untrusted software sources</h3>
<ul>
<li>From <b>trusted</b> purveyors / producers of software
<ul>
<li>These will often be digitally signed</li>

</ul></li>
<li><b>Untrusted</b> from links in spam email, suspicious third-party applications, etc</li>

</ul>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/2-2-suspiciousProgram.png" alt="2-2-suspiciousProgram.png" width="60%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 34: </span>totally not a suspicious program.exe</p>
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org78d4050">
<h3 id="org78d4050">Principle of least privilege</h3>
<ul>
<li>User&rsquo;s privileges should be kept to the lowest level required to perform their duties</li>
<li>These minimal privileges can be elevated only when absolutely necessary
<ul>
<li>This is why you go through an extra step to get Administrator / Root privileges even on your home computer</li>
<li>In an enterprise context, you <b>will not</b> have those privileges and you will have to ask for them
<ul>
<li>(unless your work for the IT department, of course!)</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
</section>
<section>
<section id="slide-orgea80b6c">
<h2 id="orgea80b6c">2.3 Compare and contrast wireless security protocols and authentication methods.</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-orgea80b6c">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgd68747e">
<h3 id="orgd68747e">Protocols and Encryption</h3>
<ul>
<li>Any wireless protocol transmits data over the air
<ul>
<li>And it can thus be intercepted</li>
<li>The answer is encryption</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgf8ef334">
<h4 id="orgf8ef334">WEP</h4>
<ul>
<li>Wired Equivalent Privacy</li>
<li>By 2002, serious flaws had been found in this protocol
<ul>
<li>Key is static and does not change</li>

</ul></li>
<li><span style="color:red;"><span class="underline">Do not use!!</span></span></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org186038e">
<h4 id="org186038e">WPA</h4>
<ul>
<li>Wi-Fi Protected Access</li>
<li>Temporary successor to WEP
<ul>
<li>Keys constantly changing</li>
<li>Used RC4 (or ARC4) simple cipher now shown to be insecure</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgc9b12dc">
<h4 id="orgc9b12dc">TKIP</h4>
<ul>
<li>Temporal Key Integrity Protocol
<ul>
<li>Frequently changing 64-bit authentication keys</li>
<li>Now shown to be somewhat vulnerable</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org69a21be">
<h4 id="org69a21be">WPA2</h4>
<ul>
<li>Currently the <b>best</b> wireless protection protocol available
<ul>
<li>Uses AES (below) and CCMP (Counter Mode with Cipher Block Chaining Message Authentication Code Protocol)</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org8d0e720">
<h4 id="org8d0e720">AES</h4>
<ul>
<li>Advanced Encryption Standard
<ul>
<li>128-bit key</li>
<li>Improves method first used in TKIP</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org46ed423">
<h4 id="org46ed423">Summary</h4>
<ul>
<li>Best encryption standard is WPA2 with AES</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgdcc201d">
<h3 id="orgdcc201d">Authentication</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-orgdcc201d">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orga77048c">
<h4 id="orga77048c">Wireless security modes</h4>
<ul>
<li>Open - no security</li>
<li>WPA2 Personal / WPA2-PSK
<ul>
<li>WPA2 with a Pre-Shared Key</li>

</ul></li>
<li>WPA2-Enterprise
<ul>
<li>Additional authentication - RADIUS or TACAS (below)</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org848e07d">
<h4 id="org848e07d">Single-factor</h4>
<ul>
<li>Simplest form of authentication
<ul>
<li>PIN or password</li>
<li>Or One Time Passwords (OTP)</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org273b329">
<h4 id="org273b329">Multifactor</h4>
<ul>
<li>Two or more independent authentication methods</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orga516f35">
<h4 id="orga516f35">RADIUS</h4>
<ul>
<li>Remote Access Dial-in User Service
<ul>
<li>Centralized authentication</li>
<li>Every user has their own identity and password</li>
<li>No password to share</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/2-3-RADIUS.png" alt="2-3-RADIUS.png" width="95%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 35: </span>RADIUS authentication</p>
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgf79e181">
<h4 id="orgf79e181">TACACS</h4>
<ul>
<li>Terminal Access Controller Access-Control System
<ul>
<li>Remote authentication protocol</li>
<li>Newer version is TACACS+</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
</section>
<section>
<section id="slide-org0a97874">
<h2 id="org0a97874">2.4 Given a scenario, detect, remove, and prevent malware using appropriate tools and methods.</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org0a97874">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org909cfe0">
<h3 id="org909cfe0">Malware</h3>
<ul>
<li>Portmanteau of &ldquo;malicious software&rdquo;
<ul>
<li>Any software designed to cause damage to a computer, server, or network</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org9b9b656">
<h4 id="org9b9b656">Ransomware</h4>
<ul>
<li>Malefactors damage your computer / network and promise to undo the damage for money
<ul>
<li>Often network drives will be encrypted by the malware, and after payment the encryption key will be given</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org9f21159">
<h4 id="org9f21159">WannaCry 2017</h4>
<ul>
<li>Global ransomware attack, hit the UK NHS particularly hard
<ul>
<li><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/may/12/nhs-ransomware-cyber-attack-what-is-wanacrypt0r-20">Link to Guardian story</a></li>
<li>Many hospitals / clinics in the UK were still running Windows XP and unpatched Windows 7 machines</li>
<li>You don&rsquo;t need to know about this for the A+ but it&rsquo;s a good story!</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org9fb783a">
<h4 id="org9fb783a">Trojan</h4>
<ul>
<li>Infected versions of legitimate-looking software
<ul>
<li>Some can disable antivirus, System Restore</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgaf565c2">
<h4 id="orgaf565c2">Keylogger</h4>
<ul>
<li>Program sneaks in to monitor and send out your keystrokes
<ul>
<li>Passwords, credit card numbers, everything you type</li>
<li>Sends it out in the clear, circumvents encryption</li>
<li>often part of trojans</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orga85e498">
<h4 id="orga85e498">Rootkit</h4>
<ul>
<li>Name comes from Unix superuser - root</li>
<li>Modifies core system files (kernel)</li>
<li>Dastardly and invisible</li>
<li>Works as root, has complete control
<ul>
<li>Only defense is prevention - once infected, it is too late!</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org736e31c">
<h4 id="org736e31c">Virus</h4>
<ul>
<li>Infect the system and replicate themselves
<ul>
<li>Usually transmitted through executable files</li>
<li>Can be harmless or extremely damaging</li>
<li>Importance of regular security updates</li>
<li>Can lead to telling slowness of computer, increased network activity</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org567509f">
<h4 id="org567509f">Botnet</h4>
<ul>
<li>Groups of computers / devices taken over by viruses / trojans
<ul>
<li>Then used to infect more machines, run DDOS attacks, or do whatever</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org19e9f95">
<h4 id="org19e9f95">Worm</h4>
<ul>
<li>Self-replicating malicious software
<ul>
<li>unlike viruses, need no human interaction to spread
<ul>
<li>Uses networks as medium of transmission</li>
<li>Often worse and harder to control than viruses</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org30530f3">
<h4 id="org30530f3">Spyware</h4>
<ul>
<li>Malware designed to spy on you in various ways
<ul>
<li>Monitors your activity, sends the information back</li>
<li>Can include keylogging</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orga5b58ee">
<h3 id="orga5b58ee">Tools and methods</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-orga5b58ee">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgaccf6cc">
<h4 id="orgaccf6cc">Antivirus</h4>
<ul>
<li>Keep it updated and running</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org117119a">
<h4 id="org117119a">Anti-malware</h4>
<ul>
<li>Can work together with antivirus</li>
<li><a href="https://www.malwarebytes.com/">Malwarebytes</a> probably the best known</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org8a7ec6f">
<h4 id="org8a7ec6f">Recovery console</h4>
<ul>
<li>In Windows 10, Recovery Environment (RE) replaced the recovery console
<ul>
<li>Powerful and dangerous, a last resort</li>
<li>Can repair many things including the Master Boot Record (MBR)</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/2-4-RecoveryEnvironment.png" alt="2-4-RecoveryEnvironment.png" width="90%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 36: </span>Windows Recovery Environment</p>
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org9c1cfaf">
<h4 id="org9c1cfaf">Backup/restore</h4>
<ul>
<li>Service first became available with Windows 7
<ul>
<li>Still in Windows 8.1 and 10</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org734cc95">
<h4 id="org734cc95">End user education</h4>
<ul>
<li>Often the most important part of prevention
<ul>
<li>Don&rsquo;t click on things!</li>
<li>Don&rsquo;t open that weird email!</li>
<li>Oh, but they just keep on doing it.</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org2b2ecf1">
<h4 id="org2b2ecf1">Secure DNS</h4>
<ul>
<li>Offered by external services, but can also set up yourself
<ul>
<li>Cloudflare, for example</li>
<li>Can block harmful websites based on lists</li>
<li><a href="https://pi-hole.net/">Pi-hole</a> is a good example of a selfhosted type (will not be on exam!)</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
</section>
<section>
<section id="slide-org0fbe00e">
<h2 id="org0fbe00e">2.5 Compare and contrast social engineering, threats, and vulnerabilities.</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org0fbe00e">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org88389e1">
<h3 id="org88389e1">Social Engineering</h3>
<ul>
<li>Can be difficult to predict and protect against</li>
<li>Changing and adapting methods
<ul>
<li>All human weaknesses can be exploited</li>
<li>Gaining inappropriate levels of trust</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org3700da9">
<h4 id="org3700da9">Some common angles</h4>
<ul>
<li>Urgency</li>
<li>Appearance of legitimacy
<ul>
<li>We make easy assumptions - uniforms, ID cards</li>

</ul></li>
<li>Intimidation</li>
<li>Scarcity</li>
<li>False familiarity</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org5bc3a1b">
<h4 id="org5bc3a1b">Phishing</h4>
<ul>
<li>An attempt to gain information by pretending to be someone else</li>
<li>Usually delivered by email or messaging system
<ul>
<li>Usually with malicious link</li>
<li>Could be Facebook, Instagram, etc</li>
<li>Message contains a malicious link</li>
<li>At first glance will look legitimate</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgeb6432f">
<h4 id="orgeb6432f">Spear phishing</h4>
<ul>
<li>Phishing with inside information</li>
<li>Use of familiar emails, formats</li>
<li>Spear phishing the CEO called &ldquo;whaling&rdquo;
<ul>
<li>Again, false legitimacy</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org6fe2ad8">
<h4 id="org6fe2ad8">Dumpster diving</h4>
<ul>
<li>Going through the garbage</li>
<li>Usually not illegal to do</li>
<li>Importance of data destruction
<ul>
<li>Shredding, destroying media</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgec3887e">
<h4 id="orgec3887e">Impersonation</h4>
<ul>
<li>Appeals to authority</li>
<li>The more keys you have, the more authoritative you appear</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org878526f">
<h4 id="org878526f">Shoulder surfing</h4>
<ul>
<li>Insecure access to screen by others
<ul>
<li>Mobility makes us more vulnerable</li>
<li>We might not be aware we are targets</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org2305b7f">
<h4 id="org2305b7f">Tailgating</h4>
<ul>
<li>Using others to gain access to restricted areas</li>
<li>Most security is at the borders</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org8e71055">
<h3 id="org8e71055">DDoS</h3>
<ul>
<li>Distributed Denial of Service</li>
<li>An army of computers mobilized to overwhelm a service</li>
<li>Large botnets can be millions of computers</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org8f93e03">
<h3 id="org8f93e03">Mitigation of DDOS</h3>
<ul>
<li>Identifying patterns</li>
<li>High grade firewall</li>
<li>ISP may have mitigation strategies</li>
<li>Again, Cloudflare has made this their business</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org5db4850">
<h3 id="org5db4850">Zero-day</h3>
<ul>
<li>An exploitation of an OS / application weakness that has not previously been reported</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgd633981">
<h3 id="orgd633981">Man-in-the-middle</h3>
<ul>
<li>Uses a webserver in-between user and destination</li>
<li>Redirects traffic</li>
<li>VPN makes you more secure</li>

</ul>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/2-5-ManInTheMiddle.png" alt="2-5-ManInTheMiddle.png" width="80%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 37: </span>Man in the Middle attack</p>
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org584d463">
<h3 id="org584d463">Brute force</h3>
<ul>
<li>Guessing passwords and usernames over and over</li>
<li>Sometimes sophisticated methods, sometimes not</li>

</ul>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images2/2-5-failed_login_attempts.png" alt="2-5-failed_login_attempts.png" width="80%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 38: </span>Failed login attempts, alphabetical usernames</p>
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org0eb3129">
<h3 id="org0eb3129">Dictionary</h3>
<ul>
<li>Checking all words in dictionary one-by-one</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org939b154">
<h3 id="org939b154">Rainbow table</h3>
<ul>
<li>Pre-built series of hashes</li>
<li>Calculations have been done for the hacker already</li>
<li>&ldquo;Salted&rdquo; hashes less vulnerable to this
<ul>
<li>(in which additional values added to hash)</li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org2df866d">
<h3 id="org2df866d">Spoofing</h3>
<ul>
<li>Pretending to be something you are not</li>
<li>Can spoof emails, MAC addresses, phone numbers</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orga9bed05">
<h3 id="orga9bed05">Non-compliant systems</h3>
<ul>
<li>Systems that are not regularly updated or patched
<ul>
<li>This leads to security vulnerabilities</li>
<li>Mitigate this by:
<ul>
<li>Regular, centrally controlled updates on network</li>
<li>Policies that prevent installation of non-compliant software</li>
<li>Monitor rogue application traffic
<ul>
<li>Firewalls, threat detection systems</li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul></li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
</section>
<section>
<section id="slide-org09eb05d">
<h2 id="org09eb05d">3.1 – Given a scenario, use the best practice methodology to resolve problems.</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org09eb05d">
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orgfd39b50">
<h3 id="orgfd39b50">Always consider corporate policies, procedures, and impacts before implementing changes</h3>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org9c73944">
<h3 id="org9c73944">1. Identify the problem</h3>
<ul>
<li>Question the user and identify user changes to computer and perform backups before making
changes</li>
<li>Inquire regarding environmental or infrastructure changes</li>
<li>Review system and application logs</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org4046b6b">
<h3 id="org4046b6b">2. Establish a theory of probable cause (question the obvious)</h3>
<ul>
<li>If necessary, conduct external or internal research based on symptoms</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org1ee895f">
<h3 id="org1ee895f">3. Test the theory to determine cause</h3>
<ul>
<li>Once the theory is confirmed, determine the next steps to resolve problem</li>
<li>If theory is not confirmed, establish new theory or escalate</li>

</ul>

<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org1c56f9d">
<h3 id="org1c56f9d">4. Establish a plan of action to resolve the problem and implement the solution</h3>
<ul>
<li>Build the plan
<ul>
<li>Calculate and document impact of solution</li>
<li>Backup / backout if things go bad</li>

</ul></li>
<li>Fix it!</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orga20815b">
<h3 id="orga20815b">5. Verify full system functionality and, if applicable, implement preventive measures</h3>
<ul>
<li>Restart the machine</li>
<li>Confirm the fix</li>
<li>Discuss with user</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-org57e8e07">
<h3 id="org57e8e07">6. Document findings, actions, and outcomes</h3>
<ul>
<li>Contribute to knowledge base</li>
<li>Useful if problem occurs again</li>
<li>In a legal sense, didn&rsquo;t happen until you document it</li>

</ul>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
<section id="slide-orge127bbc">
<h3 id="orge127bbc">A flowchart</h3>

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./images/5-1-HowToTroubleshootDiagram.png" alt="5-1-HowToTroubleshootDiagram.png" width="95%">
</p>
<p><span class="figure-number">Figure 39: </span>Troubleshooting flowchart. Seriously, memorize this.</p>
</div>
<div class="slide-footer"><br></div>
</section>
</section>
</div>
</div>
